  "prompt": "Which country does the prime minister/president have the least power over the country?",
  "response": "It's challenging to pinpoint a single country where the prime minister or president has the least power, as political structures and the distribution of power vary widely across nations. In many countries, particularly those with strong parliamentary systems or federal structures, the head of government may have limited power relative to other branches of government or levels of authority.\n\nIn parliamentary systems, for example, the prime minister's power can be contingent on the support of the parliament, and they may face significant constraints from party leadership, coalition partners, or public opinion. Countries with strong judicial systems or federal systems (like the United States or Germany) may have checks and balances that limit the power of the executive.\n\nIn authoritarian regimes, even if a president holds significant formal power, actual governance may rest in the hands of a few elite individuals or a ruling party, making the role of the president largely symbolic.\n\nUltimately, to identify a specific country where leadership power is particularly limited, one would likely have to analyze specific political contexts rather than make broad generalizations. Notable examples might include countries with strong local governance structures or those undergoing significant political transitions.",
